# Day 28 - Sudo Abuse

**Goal:** Sudo Privilege Escalation. 

**Date:** January 13,2026.


# Why this matters

- Most systems dont give attackers root directly. What they do have is a
low-privilege user account and a misconfigured sudo policy. Thats enough.
Sudo abuse is one of the most common privesc paths in CTFs and real
engagements because sysadmins make lazy decisions when setting permissions.


# The scenario i worked through

- User: analyst
- Groups: analyst, backup

- Running sudo -l shows what commands this user can run as root:
```bash
(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tar
```

- So analyst cant do much on this system — but they can run tar as root
without even needing a password. The sysadmin probably set this up so
the analyst could run scheduled backups. Seemed harmless to them.

It isnt.


# Why tar is dangerous here

- The assumption is that tar is just for archiving files. Pack some stuff
into a .tar.gz and thats it. But tar has a --checkpoint-action flag that
lets you execute commands during the archiving process.

- That means if you can run tar as root, you can run anything as root.
```bash
sudo tar -cf /dev/null /dev/null --checkpoint=1 --checkpoint-action=exec=/bin/bash
```

- That one command drops you into a root shell. The whole privilege
escalation from a low-privilege user to root, done.


# The actual problem

- The system trusted that analyst would only use tar the way it was intended.
There was no restriction on which flags could be used, no monitoring on
what tar was actually doing — just a blanket permission to run the binary.

- This is the core issue with a lot of sudo misconfigurations. Its not that
sudo itself is broken, its that the people configuring it dont think about
what else a binary can do beyond its main purpose.


# Other sudo/privesc paths i need to explore

- **SUID binaries** — files that run with owner permissions regardless of
  who executes them. If root owns an SUID binary and it can be abused,
  same outcome.

- **Cron jobs** — scheduled tasks running as root that execute scripts
  a low-priv user can write to. Modify the script, wait for cron,
  get root.

- **Writable scripts** — similar to cron. If a root process calls a script
  you can edit, you own it.

- **PATH abuse** — if a root script calls a binary without the full path,
  you can drop a malicious file earlier in the PATH and get it executed
  instead.


# What i actually took away

- Before this i thought privilege escalation was complicated. Its often not —
its just about finding the thing the admin assumed nobody would think to abuse.
sudo -l is the first command i run after getting a foothold on any linux box.
Always.